<h3 id="nunBJj"><a href="https://www.curbed.com/2019/12/4/20993584/freestanding-bathtubs-design-trends-cost"><strong>The bath bubble</strong></a></h3>
<h4 id="zvuVDE">By Magdalena Puniewska</h4>
<p id="a1Ohep">Today, this variety of tub has become the desired bathroom basin for all types of home styles, from modern to farmhouse to minimalist, and the chances of coming across a freestanding tub, digitally or IRL, are high. If Architectural Digest posts a picture of a bathroom on its <a href="https://www.instagram.com/archdigest/">Instagram feed</a>, there’s almost always a freestanding tub in the frame; recent callouts spotlight it in the homes of actors <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/Bx8Ryhvn6aX/">Jessica Alba</a> and <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/B0YXRhUn343/">Russell Tovey</a>, entrepreneur <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/BxszSYtnAY0/">Chris Burch</a>, stylist <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/BzMlrlOlyfL/">Mieke ten Have</a>, and tennis pro <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/BznmY0cnv2T/">Maria Sharapova</a>. Architects brought up freestanding tubs so often in the comments section of the American Institute of Architects’ 2018 design survey that the AIA added them as a feature to track in its <a href="http://info.aia.org/AIArchitect/2019/0308/aia-interactive/index.html#!">next one</a>. A year later, 34 percent of respondents felt like freestanding tubs were increasing in popularity among homeowners. The shift is a clue to the evolving role of bathrooms in our home lives.</p>
<hr class="p-entry-hr" id="EeqgXV">
<div class="c-wide-block">  <figure class="e-image">
  <span class="e-image__inner">
    
    <span class="e-image__image " data-original="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/13439295/PaigeVickers_CurbedLead_11_9.jpg">
      
