<h3 id="Gn8vZb"><a href="https://www.curbed.com/2020/1/15/21065962/noise-pollution-sound-cities">Sound and the city </a></h3>
<h4 id="nuw390">by Jessica Furseth</h4>
<p class="c-end-para" id="DdpL9K">More cars, more planes, more people—the argument for why the city is getting louder is strong. But it’s not like city life ever used to be quiet. <a href="http://www.documentcloud.org/documents/681856-new-york-noisiest-city-on-earth-the-new-york.html">In 1905</a>, the <em>New York Times</em> ran an article bemoaning life in “the noisiest city on earth” due to endless firecrackers, hand organs, milk wagons, and “hucksters and peddlers with cowbell distractions.” In the 1800s, Charles Dickens was “harassed, worried, wearied, driven nearly mad” by street musicians, and the Klaxon car horn was so annoying to the citizens of Chicago, London, and Paris that it was <a href="https://theconversation.com/our-centuries-long-quest-for-a-quiet-place-94614">banned</a> in the 1920s.</p>
</div>


